aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident Report for Evektor-Aerotechnik SportStar N821EV
The accident occurred in Minneapolis, Minnesota.
The accident occurred on August 31, 2014.
The accident occurred at 14:00 Local time.
The aircraft involved was an EVEKTOR-AEROTECHNIK AS SPORTSTAR.
The aircraft registration was N821EV.
The defining event was abnormal runway contact.
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was CEN14CA470.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There were no injuries to the single occupant.
The pilot maneuvered the airplane to land on runway 12 at the destination airport.
The wind was from 190 degrees at 11 knots gusting to 18 knots.
The estimated crosswind component was between 10.5 to 17.5 knots.
The pilot crabbed the airplane on a 1-2 mile straight-in approach for the runway.
Prior to landing, the pilot aligned the nose of the airplane with the runway centerline.
Prior to landing, the pilot reduced power.
When the airplane touched down, a gust of wind lifted the right wing.
When the airplane touched down, a gust of wind lowered the left wing to the runway.
The pilot initiated a go-around after the wind gust affected the aircraft.
The left wing contacted the ground during the go-around attempt.
The pilot lost control of the airplane after the left wing contacted the ground.
The pilot stated that the airplane stalled and impacted the ground.
The pilot reported that his flight school did not fly if the crosswind component was 10 knots or higher.
The pilot did not have much experience flying in winds with greater than 10 knots of crosswind.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of this accident to be the pilot's loss of control while landing with a crosswind.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined that the pilot's lack of experience flying in similar weather conditions contributed to the accident.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Minneapolis, Minnesota

## Date & Time: 
August 31, 2014, 14:00 Local

## Aircraft:
EVEKTOR-AEROTECHNIK AS SPORTSTAR

## Defining Event:
Abnormal runway contact

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
CEN14CA470

## Registration:
N821EV

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 None

## Analysis
The pilot maneuvered the airplane to land on runway 12 at the destination airport. Wind was from 190 degrees at 11 knots gusting to 18 knots. The estimated crosswind component was between 10.5 to 17.5 knots. The pilot crabbed the airplane on a 1-2 mile straight-in approach for the runway. Prior to landing, the pilot aligned the nose of the airplane with the runway centerline and reduced power. When the airplane touched down a gust of wind lifted the right wing and lowered the left wing to the runway. As the pilot initiated a go-around the left wing contacted the ground and control of the airplane was lost. The pilot stated that the airplane then stalled and impacted the ground. The pilot reported that his flight school did not fly if the crosswind component was 10 knots or higher and as a result he did not have much experience flying in winds greater than 10 knots of crosswind.

## Probable Cause and Findings
The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be: The pilot's loss of control while landing with a crosswind. Contributing to the accident was the pilot lack of experience flying in similar weather conditions.
